  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Addressing the Most Urgent Needs of Vulnerable Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) Affected by Ramping Gang Violence in Port-au-Prince, Haiti</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The increasing violence observed in Haiti from March 2020 does not appear to be close to ending. Since 1 June 2021, an upsurge in inter-gang clashes has caused the displacement of an estimated 14,000 civilians in the metropolitan area of Port-au-Prince and is having a direct and indirect impact on the whole population of that area. Gender-based violence (GBV) is reported among the displaced population, with sexual abuse, including rape, among internally displaced persons (IDPs), in host families and as an offer of &#x201C;sex for shelter&#x201D;. In response to the United Nations call for an end to the violence and CERF&#x2019;s allocation to respond to the consequences of gang activity in Haiti, the intervention aims at providing critical humanitarian assistance to IDPs in vulnerable neighbourhoods of Port-au-Prince. In coordination with other UN agencies involved in the response, the proposed intervention will focus on camp coordination and camp management and protection sectors.</narrative>
  </description>
